title: Grateful Dead Live at Hartford Civic Center on 1983-10-15
lineage: PCM -> Dat (44.1k) -> Dat (Sony R500) -> Sound Devices 744T -> Samplitude Professional v10.1 -> FLAC
description:
Set 1

Feel Like A Stranger  
Dire Wolf  
New Minglewood Blues  
Brown Eyed Women  
Wang Dang Doodle  
Big Railroad Blues  
Let It Grow  ->
Keep Your Day Job  

Set 2

China Cat Sunflower  ->
I Know You Rider  
Playing In The Band ->
China Doll  ->
Drums  ->
Space  ->
Saint Stephen  ->
Throwing Stones  ->
One More Saturday Night  

Encore
Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: electric This show was awesome, I remember when Saint Stephen  came out the energy in the whole civic center was awesome. Five stars because I was there and had a great time
And again.... Five stars because the sound is outstanding.

Probably my favorite show I simply love this show. The playing is outstanding, and Jerry and Brent (and honestly, the whole band) are just on fire the whole night. The first set has some real standouts -- Brown Eyed Women, Big RxR Blues (epic!), and especially Let it Grow - WOW. As nice a first set as one could hope for in 1983, IMHO.

The second set is even better: An foot-tappin', dance-happy China->Rider, a Playin' that spreads out into a jam that is simply AMAZING -- my favorite piece of Dead jamming form the 80', and of course the great, great Space->Spanish Jam->St. Stephen sequence. 

Now THAT's a Dead show!

I've owned various copies of this show over the years, including a nice FOB, and I feel I know this show better than any other, because for a number of years it figured very, very heavily in my rotation. Without a doubt this is the best sounding version of this show I've ever heard. Much better than the SBD, and also much crisper than the FOB I had.

THANKYOUTHANKYOUTHANKYOUTHANKYOU!!!!

Thanks for cleaning this up and sharing it :-)

Inspiring Effort Excellent show in every facet.  Great setlist and more than proficient musicianship led, of course, by Jerry.  The reviewer below me (redeyedjim) is on point with the song analysis--would only add that the Stranger opener kicks ass!!  Enjoy this puppy.

Mind-blowing sound quality Wish we would all get together in some gigantic warehouse village and enjoy this particular release as a far-out laser show.  This sounds freaking phenomenal rolling around the speakers. 
Super super sound for this great show.

AGREE I think the sound is as good as it for a few reasons  great location and the height of the Mic's.  other reason is it is still before all the bandwagon fans jumped on board with us.   Therefore creating a nice respectful sound.  Not east coast screaming and yelling.  RESPECT
Truly beautiful show, excellent, clear, full stereo AUD recording.

Great show - low audio Overall a great show. The audio is a little low but nothing an audio program can't fix. I love the Dead, and it is a bummer to see certain people on here making arrogant/snobby comments about certain section of the Dead's fans; you know who you are. If you don't like the East Coast heads then by all means don't come out here for shows. And I guess all the "johnny-come-latelys" should never have become fans because you own the scene right? Would you rather have them listen to the Dead or Aerosmith? Just a shame to see such negative/lame comments on such a great website...
Good, but there is better. While this PCM recording sounds good, the Ficca recording is even better. More open, spacious sound. PCM's tend to sound compressed in the high end, to my ears.

I Hate east coads heads I do, I think, oops I live in Massachusetts, so I hate Deadheads from southeastern Arkansas., One time I was there and I took a right turn at a darkstar and almost got beat up by a redneck. Massholes are wonderful people. I actually think shows in NY are good but oftenl ame, like the time some yahoo college students decided to take like eight rows of spaces in the Holmdel lot. I have met jerks in all states, cal Expo, NJ, in fact all Deadheads are assholes. This show is killer, should be released and mailed to me asap. Jason is coming to he fall 15 tour, not my friend Jason but the one from Friday the 13th. One time Jeff couldn't even get a paper from heads in sacramento, but that was in 78.

The Holy Grail, St. Stephen aaaaaaaahhhhh!!!  Kbmill, yes, the roar was overwhelming. I just jumped up and down the whole song, crazy fun.

It's a difficult song to play if not rehearsed often, I hear. 
This is the best of the 3 last live St Stephen.

If the band played NFA after,  whole place would have blown sky high, no survivors, so step down a bit on Throwing Stones, but what a night, one of the best, top quality nights of the early mid eighties era.
A+ Show & Recording top 5 show of the year with a warm, clear aud to go with it. what more can we ask for?
